{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}} {{Infobox film | name = Cyborgs: Heroes Never Die | image = Cyborg (film).jpg | caption = Film poster | director = [[Akhtem Seitablayev]] | producer = Ivanna Dadyura | writer = Natalya Vorozhbyt | starring = {{plainlist| * Makar Tyhomyrov * Andriy Isayenko * Viktor Zhdanov * Roman Yasinkovsky }} | music = | cinematography = Yuriy Korol | editing = | studio = Idas Film | distributor = UFD | released = {{film date|2017|12|7|df=yes}} | runtime = 110 minutes | country = {{UKR}} | language = Ukrainian, Russian | budget = $1,800,000 | gross = }} '''Cyborgs: Heroes Never Die''' ({{lang-uk|Кiборги: Герої не вмирають}}) is a 2017 [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] [[drama film]] about the [[Second Battle of Donetsk Airport]] during the [[War in Donbass]].
==Production and release== Half of the film's US$1.8 million budget was financed by the [[Ukrainian government]], and significant help was provided by the [[Ministry of Defence (Ukraine)|Ukrainian Ministry of Defence]] and the [[General Staff of the Ukrainian Armed Forces]].<ref name="RFE28903701"/>
The first official teaser trailer for the movie was released on 15 August 2017.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dVFq1VIJlog&list=LLeKnPgJYehlsEFUCXmziOpQ&index=67</ref>
It was released on 7 December 2017<ref name="RFE28903701">[https://www.rferl.org/a/ukraine-film-cyborgs-donetsk-airport-battle-premiere/28903701.html Art Of War: Ukraine Explores Donbas Conflict On Screen, In Books], [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] (7 December 2017)</ref> which was symbolically planned for the third anniversary of the fall of the old Donetsk airport terminal.<ref>http://euromaidanpress.com/2017/02/12/story-of-the-cyborgs-ukraines-donetsk-airport-defenders-to-hit-big-screen/#arvlbdata</ref>
Parts of the movie were shot in the closed [[Chernihiv Shestovytsia Airport]].<ref name="Glavcom459435">{{cite news|url=https://m.glavcom.ua/interviews/rezhiser-ahtem-seitablajev-tak-film-kiborgi-ce-propaganda-propaganda-zdorovogo-gluzdu-i-smaku-459435.html|title=Director Akhtem Seitablayev: Yes, the film "Cyborgs" is a propaganda. Propaganda of common sense and taste|work=[[Glavcom]]|date=15 December 2017|author=Yuliya Tunik|language=Ukrainian}}</ref>
==Plot== The film depicts the wartime lives of five Ukrainian brothers in arms [[Second Battle of Donetsk Airport|fighting for control of]] [[Donetsk International Airport]].<ref name="RFE28903701"/> The five men represent various social strata, professions, and beliefs for which they are willing to kill and prepared to die.<ref name="RFE28903701"/>
==Cast== {{empty section|date=December 2017}}
==Reactions== [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] commented about the movie: ''While clearly meant to drum up support for the war effort, Cyborgs isn't entirely [[propagandistic]], containing more nuanced scenes than one might expect, and [[Russian language|Russian]] is spoken nearly as much as [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] throughout the film''.<ref name="RFE28903701"/>
==Box office== The movie secured the top spot at the (Ukrainian) Box Office (earning $302,000 USD) in its opening week.<ref>[https://www.unian.info/m/society/2292579-ukraines-cyborgs-about-defenders-of-donetsk-airport-wins-the-box-office-in-1st-weekend-trailer.html Ukraine's Cyborgs about defenders of Donetsk airport wins the box office in 1st weekend (Trailer)], [[UNIAN]] (12 December 2017)</ref>
