{{Infobox person |name=Douglas J. Eboch |birth_name= |birth_date={{birth date and age|1967|12|10}} |birth_place= [[Chicago]], [[United States]] | alma_mater = [[University of Southern California]] |occupation= [[screenwriter]], [[author]], educator | known_for = ''[[Sweet Home Alabama (film)|Sweet Home Alabama]]'' }}
'''Douglas J. Eboch''' (born December 10, 1967) is an [[United States|American]] [[screenwriter]], author and [[educator]], best known for the 2002 comedy ''[[Sweet Home Alabama (film)|Sweet Home Alabama]]'', starring [[Reese Witherspoon]], [[Josh Lucas]], [[Patrick Dempsey]] and [[Candice Bergen]].<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Douglas J. Eboch|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/221728/Douglas-J-Eboch}}</ref>
His sister, [[Chris Eboch]], is a children's author. ==Career== Born in Chicago, Eboch would migrate to Saudi Arabia and later Alaska. He is a 1986 graduate of [[Juneau-Douglas High School]] in [[Juneau, Alaska|Juneau]], [[Alaska]]; while attending JDHS he was very active in the drama department, appearing in plays such as ''Helen Keller''.
His screenwriting career took off when he wrote the original story for the 2002 film ''Sweet Home Alabama'' as his Masters thesis at the [[University of Southern California]] film school. The final film would be written by [[C. Jay Cox]], and would gross $128 million domestically. Since then, he has worked as a script doctor, but has directed several short films.<ref>http://www.douglasjeboch.com/bio.htm</ref> He was awarded the Carl Sautter Award as Best New Voice, Features.
Outside of film, he also wrote the children's Christmas play ''Sleepover at the Stable...'', as well as the video game ''Night Cove''. He teaches at several schools and insittutions such as USC and [[Art Center College of Design]].<ref>http://blogs.artcenter.edu/dottedline/2015/08/18/paul-guay-douglas-j-eboch-screenwriting-partnerships/</ref> In 2016, he published a [[screenwriting]] manual, ''The Three Stages of Screenwriting'', which is broken up into three distinct phases: outlining, first draft and rewriting.<ref>http://www.screenmasterbooks.com/ttss.html</ref> He also wrote ''The Hollywood Pitching Bible'', a guide on how to pitch a film project, with Ken Aguado.<ref>http://www.screenmasterbooks.com/hpb.html</ref>
