__NOTOC__ <!-- No TOC - only Headings are see also, notes, refs --> [[File:L L Pocock Pond at Merton Abbey.jpg|right|thumb|300px|''The Pond at Merton Abbey'' by [[Lexden Lewis Pocock]] is an idyllic representation of the works in the time of William Morris.<ref>[http://www.urbanspace.com/merton_abbey_mills.html For a modern view from a slightly different spot, see the 2nd photo here] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820133552/http://www.urbanspace.com/merton_abbey_mills.html |date=2008-08-20 }}</ref>]] '''Merton Abbey Mills''' is a former [[textile]] [[factory]] in the [[parish]] of [[Merton (historic parish)|Merton]] in [[London]], England near the site of the [[Medieval England|medieval]] [[Merton Priory]], now the home of a variety of businesses, mostly retailers.
The [[River Wandle]] flowing north towards [[Wandsworth]] drove [[watermill]]s and provided water for a number of industrial processes in Merton. Merton Abbey Mills were established by [[Huguenot]] [[silk]] throwers in the early eighteenth century; there were already textile works nearby from 1667.<ref>[http://www.mertonpriory.org/history/index.html History of Merton Priory]</ref> The Abbey was restructured for [[textile printing]] in the early nineteenth century and was acquired by the artist and [[textile designer]] [[William Morris]] in June 1881 as the new home of [[Morris & Co.]]'s workshops. The complex, on {{convert|7|acre|m2}}, included several buildings and a [[dyeing|dyeworks]], and the various buildings were soon adapted for [[stained glass]] making, textile printing, and fabric, [[tapestry]], and [[carpet]]-[[weaving]].<ref>Parry, ''William Morris'', p. 57</ref> Morris refused to destroy existing buildings, and adapted them or built new ones.<ref>[http://www.mertonpriory.org/history/morris.html Merton Priory – Morris & Co] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081101073817/http://www.mertonpriory.org/history/morris.html |date=2008-11-01 }}</ref>
Morris employed a number of former [[Spitalfields]] silk weavers at Merton Abbey to produce hand-woven textiles, and used the gardens to grow dye plants and the water of the River Wandle to dye and rinse his fabrics.<ref>Wilhide, p. 30-31.</ref>
[[Liberty (department store)|Liberty & Co.]] had been involved with the site since the 19th century, as their popular ranges of fabrics for dress and furniture were nearly all made there by Littler and Co, Morris's immediate neighbours to the south. In 1904 Liberty & Co took over the Littler site, and then in 1940 the Morris facilities as well. They continued to operate the Merton Abbey Mills until 1972, and textile production was continued by other firms until 1982. During World War II part of the site was used to construct gun-turrets for the [[Bristol Blenheim]] fighter-bomber.<ref name="Merton Priory - Calico">[http://www.mertonpriory.org/history/calico.html Merton Priory – Calico] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201123235/http://www.mertonpriory.org/history/calico.html |date=2009-02-01 }}</ref>
Today Merton Abbey Mills is a [[craft]]s market and the site of a summer theatre and music festival called Abbeyfest. A number of buildings from the Morris period, and even earlier, survive, and there are displays on the history of the site. A water-mill still turns in the summer, and the "colourhouse", a mid-18th century industrial building,<ref name="Merton Priory - Calico"/> is now a [http://colourhousetheatre.co.uk/rebrand children's theatre]. The water-mill and colour house are both Grade II listed buildings.<ref>{{National Heritage List for England| num=1193882| desc=Wheelhouse at Misters Liberty's Printworks|accessdate=24 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{National Heritage List for England| num=1080891| desc=Colour House at Misters Liberty's Printworks|accessdate=24 July 2016}}</ref>
